#: Game.Doc.doc
msgid "Say we have an islander ¬ß0 who could be a knight or a knave.\n"
"\n"
"¬ß1 is represented as\n"
"¬ß2\n"
"where having the proposition ¬ß3 being true means the islander ¬ß4 is a knight and having the proposition ¬ß5 being false means the islander ¬ß6 is a knave.\n"
"\n"
"Now, we intrepret having a proof of ¬ß7 as ¬ß8 being a knight, and having a proof of ¬ß9 as ¬ß10 being a knave.\n"
"\n"
"From this, every islander being a knight or a knave is represented as follows:\n"
"¬ß11\n"
"\n"
"Knights always tell the truth, so if ¬ß12 makes some statement ¬ß13 we have that ¬ß14 being a knight implies that the statement ¬ß15 is true\n"
"¬ß16\n"
"Moreover, the statement ¬ß17 being true means that ¬ß18 is telling the truth, i.e. is a knight\n"
"¬ß19\n"
"which can be combined as\n"
"¬ß20\n"
"\n"
"Similarly for ¬ß21 being a knave which implies that the statement ¬ß22 is false\n"
"¬ß23\n"
"Moreover, the statement ¬ß24 being false means that ¬ß25 is lying, i.e. is a knave\n"
"¬ß26\n"
"which are combined as\n"
"¬ß27\n"
"\n"
"No islander can be a knight and a knave at the same time because\n"
"¬ß28\n"
"is false.\n"
"\n"
"This representation captures the rules of the knights and knaves puzzle which are:\n"
"- Every islander is either a knight or a knave\n"
"- No islander is both a knight and a knave at the same time\n"
"- Knights always tell the truth, knaves always lie."
msgstr ""

