#: Game.Doc.doc
msgid "The setting is an island.\n"
"Every inhabitant of the island will make a statement. There are two types of inhabitants, 'knights' that always tell the truth, and 'knaves' that always lie.\n"
"\n"
"We give english statements and their corresponding translation to lean.\n"
"\n"
"Given an inhabitant ¬ß0\n"
"\n"
"¬ß1 is a knight\n"
"¬ß2\n"
"where ¬ß3 is a finite set(¬ß4). Just think of this as the collection of inhabitants who\n"
"are knights\n"
"\n"
"¬ß5 is a knave\n"
"¬ß6\n"
"where ¬ß7 is a finite set(¬ß8). Just think of this as the collection of inhabitants who\n"
"are knaves\n"
"\n"
"Any inhabitant is either a knight or a knave\n"
"¬ß9\n"
"You will not have to use ¬ß10 directly but instead use the tactic ¬ß11\n"
"\n"
"Statements made by inhabitants are represented as the following for a given \"A : B is a Knave\" ,\n"
"¬ß12\n"
"\n"
"¬ß13 is of two parts.\n"
"- The forward direction ¬ß14 represents the fact that if\n"
"¬ß15 were knight then ¬ß16 is telling the truth and ¬ß17's statement is true(in this case the statement\n"
"being ¬ß18)\n"
"- The backward direction ¬ß19 represents the fact that if what ¬ß20 is saying\n"
"were true then ¬ß21 must be a knight that always tells the truth(because the other option would be a\n"
"knave that always lies)\n"
"\n"
"If you are interested in proving ¬ß22 to be a knave then you can interpret ¬ß23 in terms of that\n"
"using ¬ß24:\n"
"¬ß25\n"
"\n"
"Since knights always tell the truth and knaves always lie, no islander can be both a knight and a knave. ¬ß26 is not a knight and a knave at the same time. This is represented as:\n"
"¬ß27\n"
"You will not have to use this directly , ¬ß28 will do the job\n"
"\n"
"The objective is to conclude who is a knight and who is a knave, based on the statements of several inhabitants. This will be done using logical reasoning."
msgstr ""

